[[Image:Gallen-Kallela The defence of the Sampo.png|thumb|250px|[[Akseli Gallen-Kallela]]'s ''[[The Defense of the Sampo]]'', 1896.]]
The '''Golden Age of Finnish Art''' coincided with the national awakening during the time 1880&ndash;1910. Themes during the period were often influenced by ''[[Kalevala]]'' and were visible in [[Art in Finland|visual arts]], [[Finnish literature|literature]], [[Music of Finland|music]] and [[Architecture of Finland|architecture]] of the time.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://neba.finlit.fi/kalevala/index.php?m=81&s=82&l=1 | title = Kalevala - Suomen taiteen kultakausi | publisher = Suomalaisen Kirjallisuuden Seura | access-date = 2017-12-10}}</ref> Central figure of the time was [[Akseli Gallen-Kallela]]. Other notable figures were [[Pekka Halonen]], [[Albert Edelfelt]], [[Jean Sibelius]], [[Eino Leino]], [[Helene Schjerfbeck]], [[Eero Järnefelt]], [[Emil Wikström]] and [[Eliel Saarinen]].
Finnish art became known also in Europe at [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|Paris 1900]] World Fair, where Finnish pavilion was one of the most popular pavilions.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://kumu.ekm.ee/en/the-golden-age-of-finnish-art/ | title = The Golden Age of Finnish Art | publisher = Art Museum of Estonia | access-date = 2017-12-10}}</ref>
